<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-043-308  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 043 308.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Jan 11 1990 n1196 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Can the customer take control of cabling?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burns, Perry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer users have something to gain by urging vendors to adoptopen standards for cabling.andP;  Open cable standards would give theuser some much needed flexibility in their choice of cabling thatwould result in cost savings and enhanced efficiency.andP;  The problemis that Manufacturers such as IBM and DEC have an interest inusing unique cabling because it can help tie a customer to amanufacturer.andP;  Cabling can amount to 15 to 20 percent of the costof an installation, but by using twisted pair cable instead of thebulky, expensive co-axial cable preferred by many manufacturers,significant savings can be made.andP;  Users also need to be aware offiber-optic cable and its high speed data transmissioncapabilities as another alternative.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Hardware SelectionCablesOpen SystemsStandardization.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>